                <head>169. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In August 1960 the Soviet Government proposed that the 15th session of the U.N.
                    General Assembly be the forum for a heads of government meeting on the problem
                    of disarmament. Soviet Premier <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>
                    announced he would attend the General Assembly sessions on September 1, and a
                    number of Communist and nonaligned heads of state followed <persName
                        corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>’s lead, including President
                        <persName corresp="#p_TMJB1">Tito</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_TMJB1"
                        >Tito</persName> arrived in New York on the S.S. <hi rend="italic">Queen
                        Elizabeth</hi> on September 19 and took up residence at the Yugoslav Mission
                    to the United Nations. Anti-Yugoslav pickets convened opposite the mission and
                    loudly demonstrated against <persName corresp="#p_TMJB1">Tito</persName>’s
                    presence in the United States. On September 22 <persName corresp="#p_TMJB1"
                        >Tito</persName> met with President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> (see <ref target="#d170">Document 170</ref>). On
                    September 23 <persName corresp="#p_TMJB1">Tito</persName> addressed the General
                    Assembly and on September 28 he met with Premier <persName corresp="#p_KNS1"
                        >Khrushchev</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_TMJB1">Tito</persName> also
                    took a leading role in the September 29 effort of nonaligned leaders to arrange
                    a meeting between <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> and
                        <persName>Eisenhower</persName>. Documentation relating to the <persName
                        corresp="#p_TMJB1">Tito</persName> visit to New York is in Department of
                    State, Conference Files: Lot 64 <gloss target="#t_D1">D</gloss> 559, <gloss
                        target="#t_CF1">CF</gloss> 1766.</p>
